#Text=Nordic cuisine
#Text=The cuisines of all Nordic countries are quite similar , although each country does have its signature dishes .
#Text=Countries and regions
#Text=Denmark is a major exporter of dairy products , pork and beer , and its cuisine has a slight Central European flair .
#Text=Danes have a justified reputation of being more hedonistic than other Nordic people , eating greasy food , smoking , and enjoying more relaxed alcohol laws than further north .
#Text=Finland 's cuisine has been influenced by Russian cuisine , with dishes such as meat pies ( lihapiirakka ) , dark bread and , of course , vodka .
#Text=They are the world 's leading consumers of coffee and milk per capita .
#Text=Iceland is known for fish , lamb , and the more spectacular Þorramatur , a range of cured fish and meat products traditionally eaten during winter .
#Text=Likely the most exotic of the Nordic cuisines , Iceland has dishes that not everyone may want to try , such as lamb 's head and testicles , puffin meat and whale .
#Text=The Faroe Islands have a cuisine rather similar to that of Iceland , except it is only the long-finned pilot whale ( Globicephala melas ) that is a local delicacy .
#Text=Norway also has a heritage of seafood .
#Text=As with Iceland , Norway has a tradition of lamb dishes .
#Text=Norwegians are said to eat more pizza per capita than people in any other country .
#Text=Norway is one of the few countries in the world , where it is possible to eat whale at a restaurant .
#Text=Sweden , being the largest country in size and population , has at least one " signature dish " in all categories of food .
#Text=Some delicacies are freshwater fish , crayfish , game , berries , and the iconic meatballs .
#Text=Scania is Sweden 's breadbasket and gateway to Denmark , famous for rich meat , poultry and bread dishes .
#Text=The cuisine of northern Scandinavia and the Sami people is based on the few ingredients available in the Arctic and sub-Arctic ; predominantly reindeer , fish , and berries .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Before modern times , the majority of Nordic people had a very limited range of ingredients , especially in the far north .
#Text=Famines occurred as recently as the 19th century .
#Text=While industrialization came late , dining in the Nordic countries has become very cosmopolitan in the 21st century .

#Text=Most traditional dishes are based on what used to be poor man 's food , such as herring , dried fish , potatoes , and hard bread , although many have developed a certain refinement and are now considered classy enough for middle or even upper class people to enjoy openly .
#Text=Ingredients
#Text=With a long coastline , the fertile waters of the North Atlantic , and several lakes , fish and other seafood has a traditional role .
#Text=The right to access and easily available permits allow leisure fishing to some extent in all Nordic countries , and most restaurant menus feature some kind of seafood .

#Text=Pickled herring , ( Clupea harengus , Danish/Norwegian : sild , Swedish : sill , Finnish : silli ) , used to be the poor man 's dish , but has developed into a traditional appetizer , often in a few varieties ( such as with mustard , garlic , tomato sauce or dill ) .
#Text=Baltic herring , strömming , is the same species , though smaller , less fatty , and caught in the Baltic Sea .
#Text=Sour herring in Norway should not be confused with surströmming , Swedish fermented herring .
#Text=In Norway herring is also dried and smoked .
#Text=In Denmark and Scania smoked herring ( Danish : røget sild , Swedish : rökt sill ) is available locally .
#Text=Smoked herring from the island of Bornholm in the Baltic Sea are especially popular .

#Text=Canned sardines in oil is a traditional Norwegian product ( particularly in Stavanger that had a booming canning industry ) , but is actually made from local brisling ( also known as skipper or sprat ) .
#Text=Salmon ( Salmo salar , lax / laks / lohi ) is farmed in Norway , and used to be an everyday dish in northern Sweden , especially smoked or cured .
#Text=Farmed salmon and rainbow trout have become the most common fish eaten in Finnish restaurants and non-fisher households .
#Text=Smoked salmon , trout and other salmonid fish is served as everyday food in Norway , and can be fished with a rod .
#Text=Hot and cold smoked are two variants .
#Text=Cured salmon is known as gravlaks or gravlax .
#Text=Fermented trout , rakfisk , is a smelly Norwegian specialty particularly produced and consumed in the interior valleys such as Valdres .
#Text=Cod ( Gadus morhua , torsk ) is the most important catch in Norwegian waters .
#Text=The winter-spring ( february-april ) catch of skrei ( the migrating cod ) has since prehistoric times been the high season for coastal areas .
#Text=The fisheries around Lofoten are in particular unusually rich .
#Text=Fresh skrei served lightly boiled is a standard dish during the season .
#Text=In Lofoten and Nordland cod is also served with roe , liver and potatoes in dish known as mølje .
#Text=The cod of the Baltic Sea has been overfished , and is vulnerable today .
#Text=Wind-dried white fish such as cod tørrfisk ( stockfish ) is an ancient and important product of Northern Norway , used for lutefisk and other dishes .
#Text=Salt-dried white fish klippfisk , an important product of western Norway , is used in similar ways .
#Text=Freshwater and Baltic Sea fish , such as perch ( Perca fluviatilis ) , pike and zander can be found at some restaurants and supermarkets , and is rather easy to fish with a rod .
#Text=Roe ( fish eggs ) is a delicacy in Sweden .
#Text=The roe from the vendace , Coregonus albula ( siklöja in Swedish ) , known as löjrom , is among the most prized .
#Text=Caviar usually refers to roe from the lumpfish , Cyclopterus lumpus ( stenbit or sjurygg in Swedish , rognkjeks in Norwegian ) .
#Text=Kaviar in Sweden and Norway refers to rendered fish roe with some additives , eaten as an everyday , relatively cheap , bread spread kept in " tubes " .
#Text=Cod liver oil ( tran ) is used as dietary supplement particularly during winter for vitamin D. Bottles can be found on many breakfast buffets .
#Text=The red king crab ( Russian crab ) , Paralithodes camtschaticus , is native to the northern Pacific .
#Text=Since the Soviets implanted the crab to the Barents Sea in the 1960s , it has become an invasive species spreading to Norwegian waters , becoming a new and popular ingredient .
#Text=Crayfish ( European or noble crayfish , Norwegian : kreps , Swedish : kräfta ) is traditionally fished and eaten during August in Norway and Sweden , and among Swedish-speaking Finns .
#Text=Kräftskiva is a traditional Swedish crayfish party .
#Text=Norway lobster , sjøkreps ( " sea crayfish " ) , Nephrops norvegicus , is a delicacy of the north Atlantic .
#Text=European lobster , Homarus gammarus , is a culinary classic , very similar to the American lobster .
#Text=Shrimp , especially Pandalus borealis , have a prominent role in Norway , Denmark and western Sweden .
#Text=Clams and mussels are harvested and eaten , especially in Denmark .
#Text=Whale has a peculiar taste , and can be found in Iceland and Norway .
#Text=Whaling is a sensitive issue ; see animal ethics .
#Text=While whole meat remains a bit of a luxury , many traditional dishes are based on mince , offal and blood .
#Text=Still , all countries have lively vegetarian and vegan communities , especially among young city-dwellers .
#Text=Vegetarians face less understanding in the countryside , where hunting and fishing are popular pastimes .
#Text=Pork is the most common meat , and one of Denmark 's most important export commodities .
#Text=Pork dishes are especially eaten around Christmas .
#Text=While cattle are primarily held for milk , beef and veal are delicacies .
#Text=Lamb is a signature dish of Iceland , the Faroe Islands and rural Norway .
#Text=Several special dishes are based on lamb , for instance " sheep 's head " ( Norwegian : smalahove ) or " sheep 's ribs " ( Norwegian : pinnekjøtt , ribbe ) .
#Text=Dried , salted and smoked meat products are common .
#Text=While chicken and other poultry became everyday food only in the late 20th century , goose is traditionally eaten in Denmark and southern Sweden .
#Text=As hunting is a pastime in the countryside , game such as elk/moose , deer , and boar , is seasonally available , although mostly consumed in the hunters ' households .
#Text=Wild poultry such as grouse is a treasured delicacy .
#Text=Reindeer are traditionally bred within the Sami culture in the Arctic and sub-Arctic territories .
#Text=The meat tastes more like game than domestic animal meats .
#Text=Reindeer meat might be served as whole meat , or as sautéed reindeer , ( renskav in Swedish , finnbiff in Norwegian ) , traditionally eaten with potatoes and lingonberries .
#Text=Bread ( Swedish bröd , Danish/Norwegian brød , Finnish leipä ) is a daily staple food .
#Text=Soft bread comes in dozens of varieties , with dark , heavy rye bread of different types common .
#Text=Especially Finland , with influences from the east , has many types of traditional bread .
#Text=For more taste , try to find bread from a local bakery , instead of packed bread in supermarkets .
#Text=Hard bread or crisp bread ( Norwegian : knekkebrød , Swedish : knäckebröd , Finnish : näkkileipä ) is more known for its traditional value , than its taste .
#Text=Some types are served with cheese as dessert or snack , some are worth tasting in their own right .
#Text=Scandinavian pastries are well known .
#Text=The Danish pastry is called Wienerbrød ( " Viennese bread " ) , since it was introduced by bakers from Vienna .
#Text=The cinnamon roll presumably originated in Sweden as kanelbulle ( Norwegian : skillingsbolle ) , in Bergen it is believed to be invented there by the Hanseatic merchants .
#Text=The semla ( in Finland : laskiaispulla / fastlagsbulla ) is a Swedish pastry eaten during lent .
#Text=Saffron buns are eaten for Christmas , traditionally on Saint Lucia 's day in December ; in Sweden they tend to be known as lussebulle .
#Text=Cream cake ( tårta in Swedish , lagkage in Danish ) is traditionally made of cream , sponge cake and wild berries .
#Text=Milk and dairy products claim a large section of each supermarket , and are important ingredients in Nordic diets .
#Text=Milk is consumed both as is ( " sweet " ) and fermented ( " sour " ) .
#Text=Cream ( Norwegian/Danish : fløte/fløde , Swedish : grädde ) and sour cream ( Norwegian : rømme , Swedish : gräddfil ) are also widely used ingredients .
#Text=Rømmegrøt , a porridge made from sour cream , is a Norwegian specialty .

#Text=Buttermilk ( Swedish : filmjölk ) and " thick milk " ( Norwegian : tjukkmjølk/tettmelk ) , are sour variants of yoghurt , another variant on the theme is filbunke or fil ( Finnish : viili ) , common in Finland .
#Text=Whey butter ( Swedish : messmör , Norwegian : prim ) and whey cheese ( Swedish : mesost , Norwegian : brunost ) are other typical Nordic products .
#Text=The dominant type of cheese is hard cheese from cow milk .

#Text=Goat cheese , particularly the special Norwegian caramelised brown type ( brunost , often made from goat milk and called geitost ) , is an iconic dish of Norway . Various traditional and novel cheeses are produced , increasingly on farms that sell the products themselves or through local groceries .
#Text=Gammelost ( " old cheese " ) is a pungent and rich Norwegian special cheese made from skimmed , sour milk .
#Text=Skyr is an Icelandic dairy product , similar to yoghurt .

#Text=It is traditionally eaten in a bowl with cold milk . Skyr originates from Norway , but the tradition died out in most of Scandinavia 1,100 years ago . Skyr is produced under an Icelandic licence in Norway , Sweden and Finland .
#Text=Wild mushrooms are picked and eaten in summer and autumn .

#Text=This is however a recent tradition in most areas ; Karl XIV Johan , a Napoleonic general , who ascended the throne of Sweden and Norway in 1814 , is said to have introduced mushroom-eating to his new subjects .
#Text=Since then , the porcini ( Boletus edulis ) , one of the most popular mushrooms , is known as karljohan in Swedish .
#Text=Eastern Finland has its own older tradition shared with the neighbouring regions in Russia .
#Text=At restaurants you will mostly find chanterelles and cultivated button mushrooms .

#Text=At open air markets in Finland , at least chanterelles and funnel chanterelles are available in season ; some twenty more species were approved for sale before the market was deregulated , also other ones are often picked by experts .
#Text=Commonly picked mushroom include Boletus , Russula and Lactarius species .
#Text=Traditional vegetables are those that thrive in the Nordic climate , such as cabbage , cauliflower , carrot and turnip ( swede ) .
#Text=Potatoes have been the main staple since the 19th century , most often simply boiled , but also made into mashed potatoes , potato salad and more .
#Text=The almond potato , puikula/mandelpotatis/mandelpotet , is a variety grown particularly at high altitudes or latitudes , is a delicacy of Lapland , Norrland and Norway 's high valleys .
#Text=Fresh fruit used to be a luxury until modern times ; berries such as bilberry , lingonberry , cranberry , cloudberries and juniper berries are traditional condiments .
#Text=Apples and cherries are widely grown both commercially and in private gardens .
#Text=In Norway , apples and sweet cherries are grown in the fjord areas , notably Hardanger .
#Text=Strawberries of fine quality are produced in large quantities during July and well into August in several areas .
#Text=Traditional spices are black pepper , juniper , dill and thyme , in low concentration .
#Text=Salt has been widely used for conservation and features in many traditional meat and fish products .
#Text=It was however rare in the northern regions , where food was traditionally dried , smoked or fermented instead .
#Text=Naturally occurring herbs such as " forest garlic " ( ramsløk ) have been " rediscovered " and introduced in various products ( such as cheese ) and dishes .
